story:
Welcome to my page.

I will be taking part in the Game Heros 24hr Gaming challenge with MacMillian for my best friend's mum, Rachael Greenhill.

Rachael is an amazing, kind and caring person who gives up her time to help others. Now though she has unfortunately been struck by the horrible thing called Breast Cancer. I am therefore dedicating this 24hr challenge to raise as much as I can for this amazing person and get them as much help as they need to get through the process and back to normal life. It's also to help support her equally amazing and beautiful daughter and my number 1 best friend, Danni.

Please help and donate as much as you can spare for these amazing and wonderful people as they deserve the best that they can get.

I will be live streaming the full challenge over on my twitch channel: twitch.tv/sfrsniper1994

story:
I've decided to shave my head to raise money for charity. Technically speaking, I'm letting my kids do it. 

11yo is also cutting her locks (not shaving), and we will donate the hair to the Little Princess Trust, which makes wigs for children who are affected by illness/cancer.

We also hope to raise lots of money for CLIC Sargent and Macmillan Cancer Support. Over the past year, charities have taken a massive hit to their fundraising efforts due to Covid. Most, if not all of us will know of someone who has had or died of cancer. The charities I have chosen really make a difference and I hope that I will be able to meet my target.

story: The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: On international  happiness day I’m running! because the charity is important to me & my family
pageSummaryWhat: On international  happiness day I’m running!
pageSummaryWhy: the charity is important to me & my family
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

After losing my mum suddenly 3 years ago, the British Heart foundation has become an important charity to me.

It may seem strange that I have chosen a run called the Happy Run as my challenge in 2021 in memory of mum, but I think it’s really fitting a) because she was positive & happy little pocket rocket & b) as exercise has been so important to my mental health. 

It’s a real challenge as I’m really not a natural runner! I did a half marathon  10 years ago and done very little running since! So this will be a true endeavour. 

There is no set distance but I am aiming for as close to the 13.1 miles  as possible! 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
This is an eight day challenge and I am three days late to the party so I have five days to drag my fat arse round 500km of Scotland’s roads in the cold. Guide Dogs recently gave me Douglas who failed his puppy training so I figure I owe them one. Its a fantastic cause! 

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story: Hello everyone. My name is Bobby Gotelee. Thank you for taking the time to read this. For those who don't know me, I support Great Ormond Street through my workplace, and have been doing so for over 5 years. I am mainly known for my "24 hour in a bed" stints and my walk offs, in which I have done a fair few challenges in regards to that. This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. Now, while most people will be running off the 31 miles, I'll be walking it throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. If you ever fancied donating then all you need to do is press the "Give Now" button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever. And so this is my way of saying thank you to them, for all of the hard work they do.

story:
My New Year resolution for 2021, is to give my time and raise money for charity. 2020 has been a detrimental blow for a lot of people, but even more so for charities, with 1 in 10 charities facing bankruptcy. It is hugely important to keep pushing raising vital funds and keeping charities going, as many of them are peoples life lines.

So I’m kickstarting January by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

eventName: Row a million meters in 100 days
pageSummary: I have taken on the MILLION METERS challenge! because The ongoing  care they have provided for my son.
pageSummaryWhat: I have taken on the MILLION METERS challenge!
pageSummaryWhy: The ongoing  care they have provided for my son.
story:
We currently live in strange times and my true passion of training, teaching and competing in martial arts have been made illegal by Boris! 

Understanding how important exercises is for my personal well-being I have done more and more rowing as the year has gone on. 

I was instantly inspired when I stumbled across a guy who was just about to complete his own million challenge.

So in a nutshell the challenge is 100 consecutive days of rowing 10000m (10k). This equates to the 1 Million meters or Ashford to Berlin. 

I own a Concept 2 and have access to one at work during our training sessions. I am now 10 days in and have just completed my first 100k. Going onto day 11 I will be doing it for Great Ormond street children’s hospital. For every donation I will dedicate one of my 10k rows giving you that days row time, pace and even a dribbling sweaty picture if required as proof of my endeavour👍🏼

Great Ormond street hospital is something that is very close to my heart as they have provided my son with more than I can ever in a lifetime repay them. Should Theo decided he would like to go trough with his reconstructive surgery it is the angels at that hospital who will do these procedures.


Thank you for reading this and thank you if you can donate to a silly chap who is prepared to sit on a rowing machine for approximately 70 hours of his life it is massively appreciated.


Steve.
title: Steve's Row a million meters in 100 days  challenge

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in GOSH’s ‘Running off Christmas’ fundraiser. I'll be running every day to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity.

Your donations will support GOSH’s life saving work, which we experienced first hand in October when Sonny was taken critically ill at just 3 weeks old. We spent 10 days in the hospital and the medical care we received was outstanding. In addition to the brilliant staff, GOSH’s ability to offer parents in turmoil somewhere to stay, supplies & meals for breastfeeding mums etc is essential.

Every penny we raise will help GOSH continue to provide for other children & their families.

Thank you. Carrie, Graham, Joni & Sonny x

story: Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children STARTS HERE.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. 

I know the times are hard with Covid-19, but I am looking to raise some money for a great cause. My friend, Joel, and I will be cycling around the professional football stadiums in London. We will.be starting at Wembley stadium and follow this route: Arsenal FC, Tottenham Hotspur FC, Leyton Orient FC, West Ham FC, Charlton FC, Crystal Palace FC, AFC Wimbledon, Chelsea FC, Fulham FC, Queens Park Rangers FC and finishing at Brentford FC. This totals at approximately 70 miles. Anything is very much appreciated.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.


I decided before Christmas that I wanted to do something over the
holidays to raise money for charity.  This morning, full of Christmas
Dinner, and before Storm Bella arrived, I decided today was the day I
was going to cycle my longest ride yet (by 20 miles!) and set out to
cycle 30 miles (I ended up doing 33.4 miles) to raise money for some
charities which mean a lot to me.  It was chilly, hilly and hard work,
but I loved it!  


Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummary: Running 100 miles in January because Cancer research needs your help!
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As some of you are aware I have someone very close to me has been affected by this horrid disease and watching someone go through this is the worst and most upsetting thing I have ever experience. like many of us this year, COVID-19 has financially destroyed a lot of people’s lives and it’s affected charities. So this year I am running 100 miles in 31 days as well as 1085 sit ups and 650 push ups! 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
This year, Exeter University are taking on the incredible challenge of running the Budapest Marathon in aid of Hope of Children.

Marie Curie provide care and support for people living with any terminal illness, and their families. Last year they cared for over 40000 people across the UK.

We will be fundraising throughout the year; organising and running events, initially online but hopefully in person very soon in order to rasie as much money as possible to help the terminally ill across the UK.

Together, we can make an incredible difference to the charity's work. Rasining as little as £70 will cover the costs for someone with terminal illness to attend day therapy at a Marie Curie - which is just the tip of the iceberg for the work Marie Curie do.

Please support us and take us closer to our goals and make a difference in as many lives as possible!!!

pageSummary: I am running 5km a day in January 2021 because they supported my Mum and me during her final days
pageSummaryWhat: I am running 5km a day in January 2021
pageSummaryWhy: they supported my Mum and me during her final days
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

On April 22nd 2020, my beautiful, strong Mum passed away after courageously battling bowel cancer for 18 months. Not only was she a fantastic Mother, she was my best friend. She was a true inspiration to me and I miss her more every day. However, it is comforting to know she is now at peace and I’m sure she will be watching over me.

During the last few weeks of my Mum’s life, Marie Curie provided both her and me with practical and emotional support, particularly through overnight care. 

This last year has been very difficult for many people for different reasons, including those families dealing with a terminal illness. It is essential that these people can continue to receive help from charities such as Marie Curie. As we go into 2021, I want to try my best to raise some money for a wonderful charity that has personally helped me during a very difficult time. I will do this by running 5km every day in January.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.name: WWF-UK
pageSummaryWhy: To support wwf and because I love wildlife
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
